title: For Sale:  Custom built 300bo AR 15 pistol minus lower
postcontent: This is a complete AR 15 300 blackout pistol build being sold minus the stripped lower receiver(mine are all 80% that I finished on my cnc so I can not legally sell them). No FFL required to sell or ship. I have all equipment necessary to complete with your supplied lower if you wish. Changed my mind on this build and I am moving soon so time to let it go. This thing shoots great and was consistently shooting 2" or smaller groups @ 100yds with a cheap scope @ 3x power off a front sand bag on a cheap plastic table. That was while working up a hunting load using Barnes 110 tac tx bullets. Groups were consistent through the ladder test and I was getting right around 2150fps. All of the above is pretty damn good for this type of setup(I know I know, you shoot 1/4" groups @ 100yds off hand with a 44mag with iron sights!!) This would make a great blacktail deer rig(my intended purpose) or a great defense/fun shooting AR. I wouldn't hesitate on deer out to 200yds and most blacktail are taken inside 100yds. postcontent: Smith & Wesson 22/32 Kit Gun revolver in .22 LR. Rare Pre-model 43 Airweight kit gun, also known as “Model of 1955”. This gun for sale was manufactured circa 1955 and was part of S&W’s “pilot production” early run of this model which actually began in 1954. This gun for sale has a relatively early-run serial number of 15xxx and S&W didn’t begin mass production of this model until serial numbers beginning around 32xxx in 1958. The Model of 1955 is similar to S&W’s Model of 1953 (i.e., a small rimfire revolver with a coiled mainspring and micro-click rear sights) with the exception of the fact that the Model of 1955 is made with an alloy frame hence the Airweight name reference (Note no model name or Airweight reference is printed on gun, only its serial number). Box label includes the Airweight designation. Gun for sale is 100% factory original and is in excellent, virtually mint condition with its original factory box and includes originally factory furnished tools including bore cleaner and screw driver. No issues with metallic finish on frame/cylinder and case colored components or wooden grips, bore, sights, etc. A very slight turn line on cylinder exists but is just about invisible when a light coat of oil is applied. The Finns replaced the old 30. caliber cartridge with the more popular 9mm para by replacing the barrel with a Tikkakoski Finnish barrel which this one has a proof mark on the top of the barrel. Also this Luger has a 3 5/8 inch barrel not a 4 inch because of the Versailles Peace Treaty conditions which makes it pre WWII.  It is a military pistol as it has the 4 not 5 (which is a commerical) serial number with a letter L under it. It also has the Finnish SA next to barrel with a crown over N on the left side next to barrel wihich means its nitro proofed. And is it commerical? If you look at the history, the Finns did a commerical contract with the Imperial German Military by DWM but used them in the military. Because of the stock lug and the research I date this pistol anywhere from 1913 to 1918.
